WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.904 --> 00:00:03.320
CHRIS YING: My
name is Chris Ying.

00:00:03.320 --> 00:00:06.920
I'm the editor in chief of a
magazine called "Lucky Peach."

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:08.950
And our very
esteemed guest today

00:00:08.950 --> 00:00:13.890
is Alex Atala from Brazil,
the chef of D.O.M. and Dalva e

00:00:13.890 --> 00:00:16.230
Dito.

00:00:16.230 --> 00:00:20.410
And my job, for
whatever reason, I've

00:00:20.410 --> 00:00:22.399
been fortunate enough
to do a lot of traveling

00:00:22.399 --> 00:00:23.440
the last couple of years.

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:28.000
And one of the preeminent
experiences of my travels

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.880
was going to Sao Paulo and
eating at D.O.M. last summer.

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:34.460
And it was one of these
revelatory meals where

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:36.260
there are flavors I
had never had before.

00:00:36.260 --> 00:00:38.310
You get used to
eating things, and you

00:00:38.310 --> 00:00:41.391
see different combinations
at different restaurants.

00:00:41.391 --> 00:00:43.140
But it's really rare
that you go somewhere

00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:44.931
and there are things
that are on your plate

00:00:44.931 --> 00:00:48.010
that you've never experienced,
and flavors you've never

00:00:48.010 --> 00:00:52.420
experienced, and textures and
ideas that are wholly new.

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:54.330
You start to think
of food as one thing.

00:00:54.330 --> 00:00:58.590
So I think that's what you've
tried to capture in this book

00:00:58.590 --> 00:01:00.660
today.

00:01:00.660 --> 00:01:03.130
For those people who haven't
eaten at the restaurants,

00:01:03.130 --> 00:01:06.030
or might not eat at the
restaurants at any time soon,

00:01:06.030 --> 00:01:08.556
can you talk a
little bit about what

00:01:08.556 --> 00:01:10.680
the experience of eating
at D.O.M. is, what you try

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:12.710
to convey?

00:01:12.710 --> 00:01:15.900
ALEX ATALA: Brazil
cuisine abroad, it

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:20.140
is a huge question
for everybody.

00:01:20.140 --> 00:01:24.780
Nobody knows Brazilian cuisine.

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:28.750
And for us, it's also
difficult to express.

00:01:28.750 --> 00:01:32.940
So talking about
Brazilian cuisine

00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:36.620
is difficult, as difficult as
talking about American cuisine.

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:39.785
What is American cuisine?

00:01:39.785 --> 00:01:40.410
It's difficult.

00:01:40.410 --> 00:01:42.660
It's not just burgers.

00:01:42.660 --> 00:01:44.560
We have the soul.

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:49.840
You guys have amazing diversity.

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.762
You guys are a melting
pot of cultures.

00:01:54.762 --> 00:01:57.130
And Brazil is almost
the same thing,

00:01:57.130 --> 00:01:59.510
but we have something more.

00:01:59.510 --> 00:02:06.070
We have a place which nobody
had-- or the gastronomy didn't

00:02:06.070 --> 00:02:12.010
have [INAUDIBLE], and you
know this, which is Amazonas.

00:02:12.010 --> 00:02:19.250
This is a new
frontier for flavor.

00:02:19.250 --> 00:02:23.920
Unfortunately, in our
Brazilian culture, and maybe

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:29.570
all cultures, we always have
been looking local people,

00:02:29.570 --> 00:02:34.980
indigenous people as
a primitive culture,

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:39.990
and we didn't make lots
of attention on it.

00:02:39.990 --> 00:02:47.000
Even if they have a very
primitive or rustic cuisine

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:53.750
and culture, I should tell you
guys that that simplicity, that

00:02:53.750 --> 00:02:59.200
rusticity has been
[INAUDIBLE] over generations.

00:02:59.200 --> 00:03:06.580
There's lots of knowledge,
and lots of new ways

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:09.840
to understand our culture.

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:10.890
There's few differences.

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:18.040
I don't know if you know,
guys, but I was maybe

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:21.210
the first chef in
the fine dining world

00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:28.540
to put one ant in a
dish, in a recipe.

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:31.350
Then Scott Conant
took the same idea,

00:03:31.350 --> 00:03:36.430
and helped me to
spread this overseas.

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:40.320
Let me tell you my first
experience with ants.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:42.570
I went to Amazonas.

00:03:42.570 --> 00:03:49.930
And one anthropologist-- I
used to work in collaboration

00:03:49.930 --> 00:03:54.040
with them-- told me, Alex, you
might should meet Dona Brazi.

00:03:54.040 --> 00:04:00.190
And Dona Brazi is the local
chef in a tiny, tiny village.

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:02.440
And she didn't
have a restaurant.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:07.090
She sells food on
the street market.

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:09.120
And we went in there.

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:14.160
And she brings me a
beautiful dark sauce

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:18.320
with lots of ants inside,
and said, taste it.

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:27.690
It's tough to eat ants,
big ants, even more.

00:04:27.690 --> 00:04:29.290
We didn't learn this.

00:04:29.290 --> 00:04:37.280
But my mouth is my most
accurate tool for my profession.

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:38.670
So I might should taste it.

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:41.780
I might should challenge
my mental block,

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:44.840
or my cultural block,
and taste that.

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:45.930
And I tasted it.

00:04:45.930 --> 00:04:48.990
And I tasted the sauce,
and beautiful aroma

00:04:48.990 --> 00:04:51.470
of lemongrass and ginger.

00:04:51.470 --> 00:04:54.470
I became so impressed, and I
said, Dona Brazi, what kind

00:04:54.470 --> 00:04:56.050
of herb did you put in there?

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:58.450
And I ask because we didn't
have lemongrass and ginger

00:04:58.450 --> 00:04:59.695
in Amazonas culture.

00:04:59.695 --> 00:05:00.990
And she said ants.

00:05:00.990 --> 00:05:02.450
And I said, OK, I
can see the ants.

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:03.190
It's clear.

00:05:03.190 --> 00:05:04.810
But which herb?

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:06.010
And she said ants.

00:05:06.010 --> 00:05:07.800
And I tried to
remake the question.

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:09.200
And she said, stop.

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:10.280
Taste the ants.

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:15.460
And I grabbed one ant and I put
in my mouth, and this huge wave

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:20.810
of aroma and flavor, full of
ginger and lemongrass-- wow.

00:05:23.470 --> 00:05:28.140
And I said, wow,
I might use this.

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:32.670
So I decided to take a
few ants to my restaurant

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:34.170
and start using there.

00:05:34.170 --> 00:05:37.615
And also in my next
trip, I had planned

00:05:37.615 --> 00:05:41.380
to bring with me some
ginger and lemongrass.

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:42.405
And I did it.

00:05:42.405 --> 00:05:44.220
And I made almost
the same sauce,

00:05:44.220 --> 00:05:47.730
and I invited Dona
Brazi to taste it.

00:05:47.730 --> 00:05:51.920
And she was expecting
something new

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:55.830
from a chef who comes from
Sao Paulo, from the big city.

00:05:55.830 --> 00:05:57.670
And I gave to her,
and she tasted it.

00:05:57.670 --> 00:05:59.260
It tasted like ants.

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:05.160
First thing, first very
important thing-- for us,

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:08.610
ants taste as
lemongrass and ginger.

00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:11.480
From them, lemongrass
and ginger taste

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:17.940
as an ant-- different points
of view, different cultures.

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:21.970
And then I went back to my
restaurant with my ants,

00:06:21.970 --> 00:06:26.630
almost ashamed to use
ants in my restaurant.

00:06:26.630 --> 00:06:33.790
So I didn't have self confidence
enough to put one entire ant,

00:06:33.790 --> 00:06:39.820
and make my customer,
which is paying nice money,

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:42.740
to taste the ants.

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:45.790
So I must figure out one way.

00:06:45.790 --> 00:06:51.220
So I made powder-- ants
powder, beautiful, black--

00:06:51.220 --> 00:06:55.160
and I put it over
a scampi risotto.

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:58.370
And nobody couldn't believe
that this big, nice flavor

00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:00.360
comes from the ants.

00:07:00.360 --> 00:07:02.930
So they were looking
for the ants.

00:07:02.930 --> 00:07:04.650
And they said, it's
beautiful, but I

00:07:04.650 --> 00:07:06.802
can't find the
taste of the ants.

00:07:06.802 --> 00:07:08.260
I said, no, no it's
the lemongrass.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:12.010
They said, no, no, no, the ants.

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:17.800
I decided to make a small
pineapple, almost frozen, very,

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:22.710
very cold, with one ant,
and give to the customer,

00:07:22.710 --> 00:07:25.440
and prove this challenge.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:27.830
It's just one ant.

00:07:27.830 --> 00:07:28.690
It's just one.

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:32.220
People can face this.

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:38.680
And it's fun when you
see the expressions.

00:07:38.680 --> 00:07:40.720
It's fun, because
everybody looks

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:42.770
and doesn't feel comfortable.

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:45.400
It is a big ant.

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:49.020
And then people must take
with their hands and bite.

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:57.020
And of course, the first flavor
that comes is the pineapple.

00:07:57.020 --> 00:08:02.550
And people start to bite,
and they can't believe.

00:08:02.550 --> 00:08:04.860
And the reactions
are so profound.

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:09.990
And we are talking
now about flavor.

00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:13.905
We are talking about
emotions, how much

00:08:13.905 --> 00:08:19.670
surprise or good feelings
one food can bring for us.

00:08:24.190 --> 00:08:29.360
| or palette, is something that
we develop during the years.

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:35.640
Kids do not like alcohol,
or bitter taste, or spicy.

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:40.840
We learned how to
appreciate those flavors.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:44.540
When I was a tiny, tiny
boy, my grandmother

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:49.140
used to make a beautiful
corn cake for me.

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:57.170
And that corn cake for
me was the best flavor,

00:08:57.170 --> 00:09:01.150
or my first connection
with a good flavor.

00:09:01.150 --> 00:09:03.035
And I really became-- wow.

00:09:07.046 --> 00:09:12.340
I grew up, and we
moved to another city.

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:14.590
So I lost a little
bit the connection,

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:19.280
my daily connection with
my family, or my grandma.

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:27.110
And I grew up with always that
amazing flavor in my memory.

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:33.140
And a few years later, I could
have the possibility of taste

00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:37.800
again the same
beautiful corn cake

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:39.930
that my grandma used to make.

00:09:39.930 --> 00:09:44.830
And I tasted it, and
it wasn't so good.

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:46.105
My flavor was developed.

00:09:46.105 --> 00:09:48.540
I was not a tiny boy.

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:53.060
But until today, when I taste
something really surprising,

00:09:53.060 --> 00:09:57.470
I still think, this
is as good as the corn

00:09:57.470 --> 00:09:58.960
cake of my grandmother.

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:02.260
We are not talking about
flavor, but how much emotions

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:04.000
a new flavor can bring for you.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.190
So I try to figure out
this, both in my recipes,

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:12.540
just because I didn't
work with common flavors.

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:14.470
I work with new flavors.

00:10:14.470 --> 00:10:22.840
And the best way to
challenge, I guess,

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:25.800
should taste those
new flavor might

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:27.200
be in a very comfortable way.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:31.600
We are chefs.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:35.710
Our first commitment,
it's give pleasure

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:38.900
to people who come
to our restaurant.

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:42.240
People don't go to
restaurants for suffering.

00:10:42.240 --> 00:10:45.990
People go to restaurants
for enjoying.

00:10:45.990 --> 00:10:53.320
But we can try to give
a few more sensations.

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:57.670
So this is mainly
the way that we work.

00:10:57.670 --> 00:11:00.770
CHRIS YING: I think that's
a really perfect description

00:11:00.770 --> 00:11:03.400
of what it is to eat at
D.O.M. You're challenged,

00:11:03.400 --> 00:11:06.147
but I've been to so many meals
that are like suffering, where

00:11:06.147 --> 00:11:07.730
trying to teach you
something, and you

00:11:07.730 --> 00:11:09.180
feel like they're slapping
you on the wrist when

00:11:09.180 --> 00:11:10.513
you don't understand right away.

00:11:10.513 --> 00:11:12.590
But D.O.M. is
pleasurable, and you're

00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:16.430
educating people and educating
yourself at the same time.

00:11:16.430 --> 00:11:19.110
But that's not
necessarily the reason

00:11:19.110 --> 00:11:22.460
why Alex is one of
"Time" magazine's

00:11:22.460 --> 00:11:24.180
most 100 influential
people, whatnot,

00:11:24.180 --> 00:11:27.220
why he's built up this
reputation around the world.

00:11:27.220 --> 00:11:30.880
D.O.M. And you personally
have a bigger mission

00:11:30.880 --> 00:11:32.960
than just putting
food on the plate.

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:35.170
You have things are
more important to you

00:11:35.170 --> 00:11:37.180
than just serving dinner.

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:40.212
Do you want to talk about
some of those things?

00:11:40.212 --> 00:11:41.920
ALEX ATALA: Well,
let's take this subject

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:46.530
in two different ways.

00:11:46.530 --> 00:11:51.900
One is my message
from Brazilian people.

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:55.170
Those ingredients
that I use and you

00:11:55.170 --> 00:12:02.630
can find in my book, lots and
lots and lots of Brazilians

00:12:02.630 --> 00:12:06.510
never ever tasted before.

00:12:06.510 --> 00:12:09.450
Even Brazilians don't know.

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:14.040
So my first compromise is
show to Brazilian people

00:12:14.040 --> 00:12:19.060
that Brazilian cuisine
is a possible dream.

00:12:19.060 --> 00:12:24.610
And we have lots much
more than feijoada,

00:12:24.610 --> 00:12:26.500
or barbecue, or picanha.

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:31.010
I love it, but as you guys
in America have burgers,

00:12:31.010 --> 00:12:35.695
and it's beautiful, but
it's not whole America.

00:12:35.695 --> 00:12:36.560
We have feijoada.

00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:39.880
We have rodizio or picanha.

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:42.510
But this is not all
Brazilian cuisine.

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:44.690
And people [INAUDIBLE]
me this attention.

00:12:44.690 --> 00:12:52.520
As a colonized country,
even me, we always

00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:58.040
have more eyes for
other cultures.

00:12:58.040 --> 00:13:02.540
We never look at our
culture with pride.

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:05.030
I don't know why
Brazilian always

00:13:05.030 --> 00:13:09.550
have been looking at our local
culture as something poor.

00:13:09.550 --> 00:13:12.710
And sometimes I became
mad with Brazilians

00:13:12.710 --> 00:13:17.320
because we have fine dining,
and we have street food.

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:19.710
Street food in Brazil has
been almost forbidden.

00:13:19.710 --> 00:13:24.140
And we are fighting
to rescue this.

00:13:24.140 --> 00:13:29.920
And also something that
we call boteco-- boteco

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:37.530
is finger food that
we have just to drink.

00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:39.130
And it's amazing.

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:43.420
But people who went to
boteco used to say this

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:44.420
is not high gastronomy.

00:13:44.420 --> 00:13:46.660
It's low gastronomy.

00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:52.922
And I became-- you got it.

00:13:52.922 --> 00:13:55.890
[LAUGHS] i became mad with this.

00:13:55.890 --> 00:13:57.230
Why?

00:13:57.230 --> 00:14:00.660
Because it's cheap, it's low?

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:04.650
What do you fucking
mean, high gastronomy?

00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:09.350
High gastronomy is not to
work with fancy ingredients.

00:14:09.350 --> 00:14:11.880
It is to put one
ingredient or one recipe

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:13.550
in their best moment.

00:14:13.550 --> 00:14:17.360
And this is easy to understand.

00:14:17.360 --> 00:14:21.620
Let's make a supposition here.

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:24.810
You Americans love
burgers and hot dogs.

00:14:24.810 --> 00:14:29.100
And everybody knows where is
the best hot dog or the best

00:14:29.100 --> 00:14:31.580
burger.

00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:35.710
And those places
are very busy, ever.

00:14:35.710 --> 00:14:38.440
A sushi man in Japan
is an honorable man.

00:14:41.150 --> 00:14:48.260
His honorability is the
customer who goes to them.

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:50.580
He makes sushi for
people who have

00:14:50.580 --> 00:14:54.290
been eating sushi
their entire lives.

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:56.930
And they know this is the guy.

00:14:59.980 --> 00:15:02.120
Creativity is not
to do something

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:03.850
that nobody did before.

00:15:03.850 --> 00:15:08.280
It's to do something that
everybody does, better,

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:10.660
surprisingly.

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:11.420
This is the way.

00:15:14.060 --> 00:15:19.310
People really want to
square high gastronomy

00:15:19.310 --> 00:15:24.500
in truffles, foie gras,
small dishes, lots of money.

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:25.710
Come on.

00:15:25.710 --> 00:15:27.460
Come on.

00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:31.600
This is a fucking old idea.

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:32.690
That's true.

00:15:32.690 --> 00:15:34.860
I'm not kidding.

00:15:34.860 --> 00:15:38.260
I have much more pleasure
sometimes those mornings

00:15:38.260 --> 00:15:43.540
I went to the pier,
and I ate a sandwich

00:15:43.540 --> 00:15:47.792
with ramp and fried eggs.

00:15:47.792 --> 00:15:50.320
And that was good.

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:52.320
That was really good.

00:15:52.320 --> 00:15:56.100
That brings me surprise.

00:15:56.100 --> 00:15:59.520
I ate one egg in
an unexpected way.

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:02.730
There is something new
happens in the world.

00:16:02.730 --> 00:16:06.030
You guys from Google know this.

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:09.730
Until when we are going
to think that cuisine

00:16:09.730 --> 00:16:12.670
is only for rich people?

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:18.020
Cuisine is human,
as human as sex is.

00:16:18.020 --> 00:16:19.700
It's pleasure.

00:16:19.700 --> 00:16:22.610
It's to share.

00:16:22.610 --> 00:16:24.000
Come on.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:25.630
Food is much more.

00:16:25.630 --> 00:16:27.020
Food is culture.

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:30.220
We should rethink about
our relation with food.

00:16:34.360 --> 00:16:37.990
Talking about now about
review our concept.

