Can you talk a little bit
about what you guys do,

00:35:21.550 --> 00:35:23.600
what the institute does?

00:35:23.600 --> 00:35:28.560
ALEX ATALA: Today I was
visiting your amazing campus,

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:32.810
and someone told me that
you guys produce honey.

00:35:32.810 --> 00:35:35.640
And I became fascinated by it.

00:35:35.640 --> 00:35:40.260
Let me tell you what
we do with honey,

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:44.476
and what is these bees
that you guys have.

00:35:44.476 --> 00:35:47.670
Those bees who
produce honey that we

00:35:47.670 --> 00:35:56.090
have been eating for our entire
life, it is one type of bee

00:35:56.090 --> 00:35:58.000
called apis mellifera.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.650
If you don't know, Google it.

00:36:00.650 --> 00:36:03.060
It's easy.

00:36:03.060 --> 00:36:06.240
We didn't have this
bee in America.

00:36:06.240 --> 00:36:10.677
This bee has been introduced
from Africa and Europe

00:36:10.677 --> 00:36:11.260
into Americas.

00:36:14.700 --> 00:36:20.900
This bee produces a
huge amount of honey.

00:36:20.900 --> 00:36:30.630
And the honey is very stable.

00:36:30.630 --> 00:36:35.300
The honey that we
know has 20% humidity.

00:36:35.300 --> 00:36:40.330
That means you can leave in
your cuisine, in your kitchen,

00:36:40.330 --> 00:36:47.200
in your room, and it will be
the same product ever-- maybe

00:36:47.200 --> 00:36:49.490
crystallized, but
there is no change.

00:36:53.850 --> 00:36:59.500
Between north of
Argentina and to Florida,

00:36:59.500 --> 00:37:06.730
we have more than 500
different types of honeybees.

00:37:06.730 --> 00:37:10.180
They are tiny, tiny, tiny bees.

00:37:10.180 --> 00:37:13.010
They didn't produce
lots of honey.

00:37:13.010 --> 00:37:19.390
But the flavor of those
honeys are amazing.

00:37:19.390 --> 00:37:24.860
These tiny bees didn't have
stings, so they didn't bite us.

00:37:24.860 --> 00:37:26.170
They're called friendly bees.

00:37:28.770 --> 00:37:32.430
This honey has
medical possibilities,

00:37:32.430 --> 00:37:42.140
but for some reason,
which is healthy,

00:37:42.140 --> 00:37:49.800
security, or health loss
[SPEAKING PORTUGUESE]

00:37:49.800 --> 00:37:54.310
parameters, those
honeys in Brazil,

00:37:54.310 --> 00:37:56.860
we are not allowed to use.

00:37:56.860 --> 00:37:58.790
We can't use it.

00:37:58.790 --> 00:38:02.610
I can't use it.

00:38:02.610 --> 00:38:04.000
I use it.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:07.110
And I pray every day
for someone to arrest me

00:38:07.110 --> 00:38:13.870
because I'm using an illegal
ingredient in my restaurant.

00:38:13.870 --> 00:38:15.680
Let me try to explain this.

00:38:15.680 --> 00:38:18.150
That honey is not
legal just because they

00:38:18.150 --> 00:38:23.230
have between 30%
and 35% humidity.

00:38:23.230 --> 00:38:28.060
It is a live ingredient,
as live as wine or cheese.

00:38:28.060 --> 00:38:29.640
Fermentation happens in there.

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:36.830
Now, this is super trendy in
our [INAUDIBLE] cuisine talking

00:38:36.830 --> 00:38:39.340
about fermentation.

00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:41.010
I used to do as well.

00:38:41.010 --> 00:38:42.960
But fermentation
happens everywhere,

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:45.130
and we might [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:45.130 --> 00:38:48.630
So this is a live ingredient
that we can manage.

00:38:48.630 --> 00:38:54.540
There's no real risks for human
population in those honeys.

00:38:54.540 --> 00:38:59.990
But unfortunately, our law
has simply forgot this.

00:38:59.990 --> 00:39:02.340
In one single
ingredient, we can see

00:39:02.340 --> 00:39:07.470
all the food chain connected.

00:39:07.470 --> 00:39:13.990
If I change, or our institute
achieves to change this law,

00:39:13.990 --> 00:39:20.900
and this product became
legal, as a chef,

00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:23.580
I can have a few more
flavors, a few more,

00:39:23.580 --> 00:39:25.590
because it's not
one flavor of honey.

00:39:25.590 --> 00:39:29.800
It's a huge variation of flavor.

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:33.300
My customers, the
foodies, are going

00:39:33.300 --> 00:39:35.310
to have a few more ingredients.

00:39:38.350 --> 00:39:43.020
Medical research can also
have more possibilities.

00:39:43.020 --> 00:39:49.000
Local people can
raise these bees.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:50.780
They are friendly,
so they didn't

00:39:50.780 --> 00:39:53.590
bite kids or dogs or pets.

00:39:53.590 --> 00:39:56.230
You can have it at home.

00:39:56.230 --> 00:39:59.880
They are tiny bees.

00:39:59.880 --> 00:40:03.340
It's part of our biodiversity.

00:40:03.340 --> 00:40:05.710
It's part of our culture.

00:40:05.710 --> 00:40:09.150
If that can be income
for local people,

00:40:09.150 --> 00:40:11.140
there is a social benefit.

00:40:11.140 --> 00:40:13.970
There's economic benefit.

00:40:13.970 --> 00:40:18.180
And the last step--
bees just produce

00:40:18.180 --> 00:40:22.940
honey in a healthy ecosystem.

00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:29.650
So in one single ingredient,
you can understand all the food

00:40:29.650 --> 00:40:31.360
chain.

00:40:31.360 --> 00:40:35.430
We are trying to
make these products.

00:40:35.430 --> 00:40:37.790
So nowadays, we are
working with honey.

00:40:37.790 --> 00:40:45.040
We are pushing one project,
which is Amazonas mushrooms.

00:40:45.040 --> 00:40:48.120
It is funny that
our culture don't

00:40:48.120 --> 00:40:55.350
know about possible
mushrooms in Amazonas.

00:40:55.350 --> 00:40:59.710
So in Brazil, if you
want to buy mushrooms,

00:40:59.710 --> 00:41:04.695
you must buy [INAUDIBLE]
champignon, portobello,

00:41:04.695 --> 00:41:08.340
shimeji, shiitake, but
we didn't have our own.

00:41:08.340 --> 00:41:13.590
And natives used to
harvest, and we didn't know,

00:41:13.590 --> 00:41:16.750
or we knew but we
didn't make it.

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:22.970
So we are trying to create
a project or a meeting,

00:41:22.970 --> 00:41:28.420
but not trying to make
mushroom farms in Amazonas.

00:41:28.420 --> 00:41:34.550
We just find the spots
and put more wood.

00:41:34.550 --> 00:41:43.366
These mushrooms grow in dead
pieces, or old pieces of wood.

00:41:43.366 --> 00:41:44.740
So we are putting
them in, and we

00:41:44.740 --> 00:41:51.750
hope that after December,
in one month and a half,

00:41:51.750 --> 00:41:54.960
the rainy season
starts again, and we

00:41:54.960 --> 00:41:57.670
will see if this idea
is going to work.

00:41:57.670 --> 00:42:01.435
But I do believe that
that can be possible.

00:42:04.150 --> 00:42:05.120
I lost myself.

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:06.300
Sorry.

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:10.050
We have nowadays nine
different projects,

00:42:10.050 --> 00:42:13.470
always connect one ingredient
with the local producers.

00:42:13.470 --> 00:42:18.110
One of the most
beautiful is the rice.

00:42:18.110 --> 00:42:26.230
Nine years ago, a little bit
back, agrobusiness in Brazil

00:42:26.230 --> 00:42:28.620
is very important
for our economy.

00:42:28.620 --> 00:42:33.950
Rice production is always so
important for our economy.

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:37.390
There's a long valley between
Sao Paulo called Rio de Janeiro

00:42:37.390 --> 00:42:39.070
Janeiro called the
Vale do Paraiba.

00:42:39.070 --> 00:42:44.000
It's the first rice plantation,
or the first rice plant

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:48.350
tradition that we
have in Brazil.

00:42:48.350 --> 00:42:53.000
Almost 50 years ago, south of
Brazil starts producing rice,

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:56.220
and south of Brazil, the
ground, the soil is much better.

00:42:56.220 --> 00:43:02.800
So they produced double
amount by hectare, the valley.

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:10.460
In a country which agrobusiness
is a scale business,

00:43:10.460 --> 00:43:13.985
that valley was
already increased.

00:43:16.880 --> 00:43:21.110
They didn't produce as much,
The small producers even more,

00:43:21.110 --> 00:43:26.460
because rice was a commodity,
and they didn't have scale.

00:43:26.460 --> 00:43:30.810
So they have been pushed
from their own land.

00:43:30.810 --> 00:43:35.930
One researcher,
or one scientist,

00:43:35.930 --> 00:43:42.390
which we call breeder,
decided to convince

00:43:42.390 --> 00:43:45.410
one small producer
to plant black rice.

00:43:45.410 --> 00:43:49.260
Just to let you know, guys,
in Brazil, in the old days,

00:43:49.260 --> 00:43:57.010
black rice was considered a
disease, a rice disease, OK?

00:43:57.010 --> 00:44:00.470
This breeder has
convinced this young guy

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:01.950
to produce this black rice.

00:44:01.950 --> 00:44:03.290
And they made it.

00:44:03.290 --> 00:44:04.880
And they have a huge success.

00:44:04.880 --> 00:44:08.730
They harvested a
huge amount of rice.

00:44:08.730 --> 00:44:12.100
The problem was, nobody
wants to buy black rice.

00:44:12.100 --> 00:44:18.090
For our culture, black
rice is not a good rice.

00:44:18.090 --> 00:44:20.510
They became a complete loss.

00:44:20.510 --> 00:44:24.500
So they decided-- this
is a true history--

00:44:24.500 --> 00:44:30.350
they decided to buy gastronomic
magazines, and they found me.

00:44:30.350 --> 00:44:33.420
So one day I was in my
restaurant nine years ago.

00:44:33.420 --> 00:44:35.170
They touched at my door.

00:44:35.170 --> 00:44:37.470
I opened the door.

00:44:37.470 --> 00:44:48.350
It was a small producer, very
dressed as a countryside guy,

00:44:48.350 --> 00:44:50.900
and this researcher.

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:52.470
They gave me this black rice.

00:44:52.470 --> 00:44:54.740
Please, help us, they said.

00:44:54.740 --> 00:44:58.180
I tasted it, and the texture
and flavor was beautiful.

00:44:58.180 --> 00:45:00.590
So I started to use
in the same day.

00:45:00.590 --> 00:45:04.380
And I started to talk with
other chefs, and thank God,

00:45:04.380 --> 00:45:10.260
the Brazilian press has also
talked largely about this rice.

00:45:10.260 --> 00:45:14.870
Nowadays, this rice
has spread everywhere,

00:45:14.870 --> 00:45:16.370
really everywhere,
even in Amazonas.

00:45:20.430 --> 00:45:25.310
Between three and four years
ago, this breeder got cancer.

00:45:25.310 --> 00:45:28.220
And he knew that
he was terminal.

00:45:28.220 --> 00:45:32.230
So he called me and said,
Alex, come to is visit me.

00:45:32.230 --> 00:45:34.260
I want to talk with you.

00:45:34.260 --> 00:45:37.555
I went in there, and he showed
me a tiny, tiny, tiny bowl

00:45:37.555 --> 00:45:44.460
of rice, ball-shaped rice,
and said please, do something

00:45:44.460 --> 00:45:45.500
with this.

00:45:45.500 --> 00:45:49.130
I'm going to pass away, and
this is my last research.

00:45:51.840 --> 00:45:54.100
We made it.

00:45:54.100 --> 00:45:59.490
Nowadays, this rice is,
again, spread in everywhere.

00:45:59.490 --> 00:46:02.620
But the beautiful, the
most beautiful history,

00:46:02.620 --> 00:46:06.250
or beautiful goal
of this history

00:46:06.250 --> 00:46:09.100
is not the black rice
or the small rice.

00:46:09.100 --> 00:46:13.340
All the valley nowadays
is not planting

00:46:13.340 --> 00:46:19.250
black rice or mini rice.

00:46:19.250 --> 00:46:23.210
All the small producers
are planting special rice.

00:46:23.210 --> 00:46:27.900
I mean koshihikari,
Japanese rice, jasmine rise,

00:46:27.900 --> 00:46:30.790
basmati rice.

00:46:30.790 --> 00:46:32.905
They realized
something very simple.

00:46:35.540 --> 00:46:38.520
Big wines, big cheeses
in Europe are not

00:46:38.520 --> 00:46:39.840
produced by big companies.

00:46:42.590 --> 00:46:46.040
Producing quality can
be the biggest goal

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:50.110
for a small producer,
if the market pays.

00:46:54.740 --> 00:47:01.690
Our dream in Ata is keep
doing things like this.

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:04.330
This project with
the rice, for me,

00:47:04.330 --> 00:47:11.820
it's very meaningful,
because the biggest goal

00:47:11.820 --> 00:47:15.360
it is to change
one local culture.

00:47:15.360 --> 00:47:20.710
We are learning something more
which is very tough for us.

00:47:20.710 --> 00:47:24.240
We created a label, which
is called Retratas do Gosto.

00:47:24.240 --> 00:47:30.220
That means faces of flavor,
maybe something like this.

00:47:30.220 --> 00:47:38.560
And we give all support
for local people

00:47:38.560 --> 00:47:43.130
if they produce a good
ingredient, healthy ingredient.

00:47:43.130 --> 00:47:49.190
And we to package and
to sell everything.

00:47:49.190 --> 00:47:51.720
And we have benefits,
economic benefits.

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:58.300
25% of our benefits, might
go back to the lands,

00:47:58.300 --> 00:48:00.100
not for the producer.

00:48:00.100 --> 00:48:03.510
So you with the black
rice, what we did

00:48:03.510 --> 00:48:09.460
was build a new
research center, not

00:48:09.460 --> 00:48:11.860
to help only the
guys who were already

00:48:11.860 --> 00:48:17.210
planting black rice or
small rice or mini rice,

00:48:17.210 --> 00:48:21.420
guys who are not included
in our philosophy

00:48:21.420 --> 00:48:25.360
to plant different
rice or special rice.

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:32.490
The next step, try to convince
them to plant organic rice.

00:48:32.490 --> 00:48:35.740
And let me explain why.

00:48:35.740 --> 00:48:40.060
These small producers
sometimes need money.

00:48:40.060 --> 00:48:43.230
They might go to the bank.

00:48:43.230 --> 00:48:48.640
The bank might
guarantee his money.

00:48:48.640 --> 00:48:51.330
And the only way that
the bank can believe,

00:48:51.330 --> 00:48:56.000
and also the small producer
believe that the harvest will

00:48:56.000 --> 00:49:05.490
be safe, and they can pay back
the bank, is buying chemicals.

00:49:05.490 --> 00:49:11.120
So when a Brazilian small
producer signs a bank contract,

00:49:11.120 --> 00:49:18.370
it's included that he might
buy those specific seeds that

00:49:18.370 --> 00:49:23.760
come from a big company,
and those chemicals that

00:49:23.760 --> 00:49:27.020
come from another company.

00:49:27.020 --> 00:49:30.560
This is a cultural barrier.

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:34.300
Those guys, I can't
blame them, the bank

00:49:34.300 --> 00:49:38.190
or the small producers.

00:49:38.190 --> 00:49:39.810
It is just a cultural barrier.

00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:45.470
They didn't believe that
organic food is a possible way.

00:49:45.470 --> 00:49:48.760
They don't know.

00:49:48.760 --> 00:49:57.430
How can one bank be convinced
that organic agriculture

00:49:57.430 --> 00:50:06.770
is something real, if
there are companies

00:50:06.770 --> 00:50:11.870
who support money
to sell chemicals?

00:50:11.870 --> 00:50:14.900
And nobody can
explain to them how

00:50:14.900 --> 00:50:20.860
we can change the culture
from the local people,

00:50:20.860 --> 00:50:28.250
if the last 15 years, they
only learned to put chemicals,

00:50:28.250 --> 00:50:31.160
and nobody knows
anymore how to--

00:50:31.160 --> 00:50:36.310
So it is our
commitment nowadays,

00:50:36.310 --> 00:50:46.750
is to try to improve
the food chain,

00:50:46.750 --> 00:50:51.260
organize, revalue,
and trying to not make

00:50:51.260 --> 00:50:54.560
big changes in the food web.

00:50:57.670 --> 00:51:01.380
It is two very difficult
lines, but we keep trying.

00:51:01.380 --> 00:51:03.340
And I don't know if
we will be successful,

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:06.930
but it's our challenge.

00:51:06.930 --> 00:51:08.930
AUDIENCE: You were talking
before about the size

00:51:08.930 --> 00:51:11.013
of the United States, and
that it's a melting pot,

00:51:11.013 --> 00:51:13.600
and that there's so many
different flavors here.

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:16.700
And I think about the
size of the Amazon,

00:51:16.700 --> 00:51:19.500
and it's humongous
on the scale that's

00:51:19.500 --> 00:51:22.820
difficult to comprehend,
which would tend

00:51:22.820 --> 00:51:26.120
to make me think that throughout
there, even the native cultures

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:27.900
are going to have
a lot of variations

00:51:27.900 --> 00:51:31.200
and different flavors
and different styles.

00:51:31.200 --> 00:51:35.630
And how has that
affected your cooking?

00:51:35.630 --> 00:51:37.175
ALEX ATALA: Well,
this on one hand

00:51:37.175 --> 00:51:40.600
gives us more possibilities.

00:51:40.600 --> 00:51:45.080
So it's on one hand
super exciting.

00:51:45.080 --> 00:51:51.870
Of course, when you
have this big melting

00:51:51.870 --> 00:51:58.760
pot, which we are as
well, it is not so easy.

00:52:02.580 --> 00:52:12.200
But why do you stop your
car when the sign is red?

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:15.200
It is not to not crash your car.

00:52:15.200 --> 00:52:20.300
Is for benefits for the
whole entire community,

00:52:20.300 --> 00:52:21.430
to help traffic.

00:52:24.430 --> 00:52:29.480
I mean, this is the
most simple thing.

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:31.610
We might to believe
that it's possible.

00:52:31.610 --> 00:52:36.310
If you start to do, someone
is going to start to do,

00:52:36.310 --> 00:52:39.010
and this creates a kind of wave.

00:52:39.010 --> 00:52:42.420
Chefs nowadays have
more voice than ever.

00:52:46.010 --> 00:52:51.050
Our first commitment, of
course, is make nice food

00:52:51.050 --> 00:52:52.850
for customers.

00:52:52.850 --> 00:52:56.640
But we can go one step forward.

00:52:56.640 --> 00:52:59.890
We can try to provoke
a few changes.

00:52:59.890 --> 00:53:03.160
If I have a voice, I can
have more voice to say,

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:04.260
look how beautiful I am.

00:53:04.260 --> 00:53:09.890
Or I can have more voice
to spread another message.

00:53:09.890 --> 00:53:16.040
And we are trying to do this.

00:53:16.040 --> 00:53:22.280
I don't know if it's too
romantic, almost utopic.

00:53:22.280 --> 00:53:26.420
But man, when I
went in the kitchen,

00:53:26.420 --> 00:53:29.630
nobody wants you to be a chef.

00:53:29.630 --> 00:53:31.160
I was a punk rocker.

00:53:31.160 --> 00:53:35.230
Nobody wanted to give
a job for myself.

00:53:35.230 --> 00:53:39.050
So I can keep going.

